'''Korn''' (styled as '''Ko<U+042F>n'''<ref name="Ko<U+042F>n official website">{{cite web|url = http://modlife.com/korn|publisher = Modlife, Inc.|title = Ko<U+042F>n|author = Ko<U+042F>n|accessdate = 2010-04-21}}</ref>) is an American [[nu metal music|nu metal]] band from [[Bakersfield, California]], formed in 1993. The current band line up includes four members: [[Jonathan Davis]], [[James Shaffer|James "Munky" Shaffer]], [[Reginald Arvizu|Reginald "Fieldy" Arvizu]], and [[Ray Luzier]]. The band was formed as an expansion of [[L.A.P.D. (band)|L.A.P.D.]] They have collaborated with musicians such as [[Chino Moreno]] from [[Deftones]], [[Fred Durst]] from [[Limp Bizkit]], [[Ice Cube]], Tre Hardson from [[The Pharcyde]] and [[Nas]].

The band released their first [[demo album]], ''[[Neidermeyer's Mind]]'', in 1993.<ref name="small 16"/> Their debut album, ''[[Korn (album)|Korn]]'' was released in 1994, where they featured the same musicians that had performed on ''Neidermeyer's Mind''. The band began recording ''[[Life Is Peachy]]'' in April 1996, and released it on October 15, 1996. ''[[Follow the Leader (Korn album)|Follow the Leader]]'' is recognized as Korn's mainstream breakthrough, peaking at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in 1998, along with the following album, ''[[Issues (Korn album)|Issues]]'' in 1999.<ref name="Billboard 200 albums">[http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/korn/chart-history/121196?f=305&g=Albums Korn Album & Song Chart History] Billboard.com. Retrieved 2010-03-10.</ref> The band released ''[[Untouchables (album)|Untouchables]]'' on June 11, 2002, and later released ''[[Take a Look in the Mirror]]'' on November 21, 2003, both peaking in the top ten of the ''Billboard'' 200. Their first [[compilation album]], ''[[Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 (Korn album)|Greatest Hits Vol. 1]]'', peaked at number four on the ''Billboard'' 200. ''[[See You on the Other Side (Korn album)|See You on the Other Side]]'' was released on December 6, 2005, and [[Untitled Korn album|Korn's untitled album]] was released nearly two years later on July 31, 2007. ''[[Korn III: Remember Who You Are]]'', the band's ninth studio album, was released July 13, 2010 via Roadrunner Records.<ref name="munky">{{cite web|url = http://www.backstageaxxess.com/index.php/interviews/50-munkyofkorn|publisher = BackstageAxxess.com|title = Guitarist Munky of Korn |author = Gus Griesinger |accessdate = 2009-06-06}}</ref> Korn currently has 36 [[single (music)|singles]], 25 of which have charted.<ref name="Billboard 200 albums"/><ref name="aus-2">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/search.asp?search=Korn&cat=s|title=Australian singles chart|publisher=australian-charts.com|accessdate=2010-03-10}}</ref><ref name="uk">{{cite web
| url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK_K.HTM
| title=British chart
| publisher=Zobbel.de
| accessdate=2010-03-10}}</ref> The band has six video albums and 32 music videos.

Korn has sold 16 million albums in the US, and over 38 million worldwide.<ref name="riaa">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=tblTopArt&action=|title=Top Selling Artists|accessdate=2007-11-04|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]}}</ref> Ten of the band's official releases have peaked in the top ten of the ''Billboard'' 200, eight of which have peaked in the top five.<ref name="Billboard 200 albums" /> Eight of those releases are certified Platinum by the [[RIAA]], and one is certified Gold.<ref>{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Korn|type=album}}</ref> Korn have also earned seven [[Grammy Awards|Grammy]] nominations <U+2014> two of which they have won (for "[[Freak on a Leash]]" and "[[Here to Stay (Korn song)|Here to Stay]]").<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p144403|pure_url=yes}}|title=GRAMMY Awards|accessdate=2007-12-06|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]}}</ref><ref name="roadrunnerrecords1">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=150243 |title=Blabbermouth.Net - Iron Maiden, Slayer, Megadeth, Ozzy, Korn Among Grammy Awards Nominees |publisher=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date= |accessdate=2010-12-08}}</ref>

==History==
===L.A.P.D. and formation (1989<U+2013>93)===
Before Korn was formed, three of the original members of the band were associated with the [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[L.A.P.D. (band)|L.A.P.D.]]: [[James Shaffer]], [[Reginald Arvizu]], and [[David Silveria]].<ref>Torreano, Bradley [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p13443|pure_url=yes}} allmusic ((( L.A.P.D. > Overview )))] Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-05-11.</ref><ref name="arvizu 36">{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=36}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=37}}</ref> Originally consisting of Richard Morrill, James Shaffer, and Reginald Arvizu, David Silveria joined when he was 15.<ref name="arvizu 36"/> The band moved their location from [[Bakersfield, California]] to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. As a result, Silveria dropped out of high school and Shaffer stayed in Bakersfield.<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=38}}</ref> When Shaffer reunited with the band, the band found a manager and released an EP entitled ''Love and Peace Dude'' in 1989 through [[Triple X Records]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=50}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=53}}</ref> L.A.P.D. released their first full-length [[studio album]] on May 3, 1991 which consisted of eleven tracks. The album was entitled ''[[Who's Laughing Now]]''.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r11282|pure_url=yes}} allmusic ((( Who's Laughing Now > Overview )))] Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-05-11.</ref> After releasing their two albums, L.A.P.D. broke up and Shaffer, Arvizu, and Silveria, along with [[Brian Welch]] and [[Jonathan Davis]] formed a band later to be known as "Korn".<ref name="arvizu 53-71">{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|pp=53<U+2013>71}}</ref>

{{Listen
|filename=Korn - Predictable (demo).ogg
|title="Predictable" (1993)
|description=30 second sample from the song "Predictable" which the band would eventually re-make on their debut album. ''Neidermeyer's Mind'' featured the first captured, recorded sound of Korn in the form of four tracks.<ref name="small 16"/>}}
Korn achieved its name after a fan suggested the name "Corn". At first, the group rejected the idea, but later, with no alternate names, the group selected the name "Corn". Later, Shaffer suggested spelling their name with a "K" instead of a "C", and Shaffer came up with the idea to reverse the "R", so the band's name would appear as "Ko<U+042F>n".<ref name="arvizu 53-71"/> The logo was designed by [[singing|lead vocalist]] [[Jonathan Davis]].<ref name="small 16"/> Silveria explained, "the music makes the name, because Korn's a dumb name. But once we get established, it makes the name cool."<ref name="Small 1998 p. 16"/>

At [[Huntington Beach, California]], Korn rented a studio from Jeff Creath, called "Underground Chicken Sound." While they were recording at Underground Chicken Sound, a crowd had been [[loitering]] outside the studio.<ref name="fieldy 63">{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=63}}</ref> The band began playing a prelude to a later song, "Clown" resulting in a larger crowd gathering. Arvizu said the crowd gathered because it sounded so "different."<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=64}}</ref> Korn started performing at gigs in the summer of 1993, with members saying that touring was a "pain-in-the-ass." While in Huntington Beach, the band was spotted by Epic/Immortal Records A&R employee Paul Pontius. Pontius would describe Korn's sound as "the new genre of rock." In 1993, Korn released their first [[demo album]], ''[[Neidermeyer's Mind]]''. Their album had very limited printing, and was never well received by critics or fans.<ref name="small 16">{{Harvnb|Small|1998|p=16}}</ref> It was released to [[record companies]] and to people who filled out a flyer given out at gigs they played for free with [[Biohazard (band)|Biohazard]] and [[House of Pain]].<ref name="Small 1998 p. 16">Small 1998 p. 16</ref>

===Debut album (1994<U+2013>95)===
By May 1994, Korn began recording their [[Korn (album)|debut album]] with [[Ross Robinson]].<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r218075|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Korn > Credits )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-16.</ref> On October 11, 1994, Korn released a self<U+2013>titled album through [[Immortal Records|Immortal]]/[[Epic Records|Epic]],<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r218075|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Korn > Overview )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-16.</ref> which eventually peaked at number 72 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in 1995, as well as peaking number one on [[Top Heatseekers]] chart.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r218075|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Korn > Chart & Awards )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-16.</ref> The album received positive reviews by critics, and it is said to have established the [[nu metal|new wave of metal]].<ref name="nu metal">{{cite book |last=McIver |first=Joel |title=Nu-metal: The Next Generation of Rock & Punk |year=2002 |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=0711992096 |page=23}}</ref><ref name="arnopp">{{Cite book |last = Arnopp |first = Jason |title = Slipknot: Inside the Sickness, Behind the Masks |publisher = Ebury |year = 2001 |isbn = 0091879337 |pages=6<U+2013>7|postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> As well as sparking the nu metal genre, the album also started [[record producer]] Ross Robinson's music career.<ref name="nu metal"/> It also influenced other bands, like [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Coal Chamber]], and [[Limp Bizkit]].<ref name="nu metal"/><ref name="arnopp"/>

After Korn finished recording the album, they began touring with [[Biohazard (band)|Biohazard]]. Their record company gave them enough money for their own tour bus. Korn's first gig was in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=74}}</ref> About half way through the tour, their tour bus that their record company gave them stopped working, and Korn had to find a new one.<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=77}}</ref> Their first tour was not very successful in promoting the album.<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=78}}</ref> Korn started the [[Sick of It All]] Tour in January 1995.<ref>Arvizu 2009 p. 81</ref> Aside from touring, Korn released four singles. "[[Blind (Korn song)|Blind]]" was released in 1994, and "[[Shoots and Ladders (song)|Shoots and Ladders]]" was released in 1995. The latter received a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nomination in 1997 for [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance|Best Metal Performance]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960105&slug=2307442|title=Presidents of the U.S. are riding high in the musical polls |last=MacDonald|first=Patrick|date=January 5, 1996|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=December 17, 2009}}</ref> "[[Need To]]" was also released in 1995, although the exact date is unknown. The fourth and final single, "[[Clown (song)|Clown]]," was released in 1996. As of 2010, none of the singles have ever charted.<ref name="us">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/korn/chart-history/121196|title=American chart|publisher=[[Billboard charts]]|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref>

===''Life Is Peachy'' (1996<U+2013>97)===
After the success of their debut, Korn decided to enter the studio again for a second album.<ref name="arvizu 78">Arvizu 2009 p. 78</ref> By then, the band had created a large [[Fan (person)|fan base]], and the expectations for their follow up album were high.<ref name="arvizu 78"/><ref name="R-U"/> They went back into the studio in early April 1996 at Indigo Ranch Studios, [[Malibu, California]].<ref name="arvizu 78"/> {{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center
 |quote = <U+2026>We went in really fresh, and we wanted to get it done quickly to capture that energy. So it was probably about 60% knowing what I was going to play and 40% just playing whatever came to mind at that moment<U+2026> It ended up really good, and it has a kind of energy I probably wouldn't have gotten if I'd worked everything out before hand.
 |source = David Silveria on ''Life Is Peachy''{{'}}s drum quality.<ref name="Small 30"/>
 |width = 30%
 |align = left
}}The album was released October 15, 1996,<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r241493|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Life Is Peachy > Overview )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-09-04.</ref> and despite minimal radio airplay and television attention, ''[[Life Is Peachy]]'' debuted at number three on the ''Billboard'' 200,<ref name="arvizu 78"/><ref name="Small 30">Small 1998 p. 30</ref> and peaked at number one on the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|Recording Industry Association of New Zealand sales chart]].<ref>[http://charts.org.nz/search.asp?search=Korn&cat=a "New Zealand charts portal"]. Charts.org. Retrieved 2010-09-04.</ref> The album sold 106,000 copies in its first week.<ref>Arvizu 2009 p. 79</ref> [[Jon Pareles]] from ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that the band was "Mad at Everybody, Including Themselves." The album was certified a 2<U+00D7> Platinum in the United States,{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Korn|type=album|title=Life Is Peachy}} Platinum in Australia{{Certification Cite Ref|region=Australia|artist=Korn|type=album|title=Life Is Peachy|certyear=1999}} and Gold in Canada.<ref name="cria">{{cite web|url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php|title=CRIA certifications|accessdate=2008-03-21|publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]]}}</ref>

The first single, "[[No Place to Hide (song)|No Place to Hide]]", spawned a Grammy nomination for Best Metal Performance.<ref>Lewis, Randy. (1998-01-07). [http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/1998/02/22/1998-02-22_lining_up_grammy_s_hit_list_.html "Strong O.C. Pack in Hunt for Grammys; Awards: No Doubt earns two nominations, including 'Don't Speak' in the song category. Orchestra's Danielpour also scores."]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> "[[A.D.I.D.A.S.]]" was the second single and only music video from the album, which also did well, and earned the band the most airplay until their next album's singles.<ref>Small 1998 p. 32</ref> The band gained more popularity after co-headlining the [[Lollapalooza]] music festival in 1997 with [[Tool (band)|Tool]]. However, Korn was forced to stop touring after Shaffer was diagnosed with [[Meningitis#Viral meningitis|viral meningitis]].<ref name="lollapalooza-illness">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431015/19970801/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Off Lolla Due To Guitarist's Illness|date=1997-08-01|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> A promotional disc was released in 1997 to promote both the band and the ''Life Is Peachy'' Tour featuring [[Incubus (band)|Incubus]] and [[The Urge]] and included three live tracks.<ref>{{cite album-notes |title=Korn: Life Is Peachy Tour Sampler |albumlink=Life Is Peachy |artist=Korn |year=1997 |format=CD |publisher=[[Sony Music Entertainment]] |publisherid= |location=Europe |ref= }}</ref>

===''Follow the Leader'', mainstream success (1998<U+2013>99)===
{{Listen
|filename=Korn - Freak on a Leash.ogg
|title="Freak on a Leash" (1998)
|description=Both "Freak on a Leash" and "Got the Life" are both considered to be the first music videos retired from [[MTV]].<ref name="Arvizu 118"/> The song was a "rolling exorcism."<ref>(1998-11-02) [http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2_IaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4EcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6370,131296&dq=follow+the+leader+korn&hl=en "Korn puts on dancing shoes in new album"] ''Daily News''. Retrieved 2010-03-20.</ref>}}
Prior to the release of the band's third album, Korn produced a weekly online TV show, KornTV,<ref name="Arvizu 112">{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=112}}</ref><ref name="korn-tv">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431011/19980302/korn.jhtml|title=Korn To Do It Themselves On "Korn TV"|date=1998-03-02|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> which documented the making of the record and featured special guests such as [[porn star]] [[Ron Jeremy]], [[Limp Bizkit]], and [[311 (band)|311]].<ref name="korn-tv"/> The project also gave fans the chance to call in and ask the band questions, an approach that represented one of the first times a band utilized the Internet in such a way.<ref name="follow the leader notes"/> Korn released their third album, ''[[Follow the Leader (Korn album)|Follow the Leader]]'', on August 18, 1998,<ref>(1998-07-29) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430857/19980715/kiss.jhtml "Spawn-Master McFarlane Hooks Up With Korn, Kiss"]. MTV. Retrieved 2010-07-08.</ref> which featured a number of guest vocalists such as [[Ice Cube]], [[Tre Hardson]] from the [[Pharcyde]], [[Fred Durst]] of Limp Bizkit and actor [[Cheech Marin]] on the hidden track "Earache My Eye" (written by Marin himself).<ref name="follow the leader notes">{{cite album-notes |title=Follow the Leader |albumlink=Follow the Leader (Korn album) |artist=Korn |year= 1998 |format=[[Compact Disc]] |publisher= Immortal/Epic}}</ref>

Korn launched a political campaign-style tour to promote the release of ''Follow the Leader''.<ref name="Arvizu 114"/><ref name="kampaign">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430999/19980817/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Kicks Off Kampaign '98 In Los Angeles|date=1998-08-17|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> The tour took the group, on a chartered jet, all over North America to help promote ''Follow the Leader''.<ref name="Arvizu 114"/> They talked to fans and answered questions during special "fan conferences", which were organized at every stop along the tour route, and signed autographs. Jim Rose hosted the entire "Kampaign" tour.<ref name="Arvizu 114"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=115}}</ref>

The album was considered by band members a complete success, debuting at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 with 268,000 copies sold,<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=113}}</ref><ref name="ftl-first-week">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430996/19980826/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Tops Album Heap In Chart Debut|date=1998-08-26|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> and spawning two of their biggest [[single (music)|singles]]: "[[Got the Life]]" and "[[Freak on a Leash]]".<ref name="Arvizu 114">{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=114}}</ref> They both exposed Korn to a wider, mainstream audience, with the music videos being mainstays on MTV's ''[[Total Request Live]]''. "Got the Life" was the show's very first "retired" video,<ref name="Arvizu 118">{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=118}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|pp=146<U+2013>147}}</ref><ref>''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''. March 2000. p. 64</ref> with "Freak on a Leash" reaching that same success months later.<ref name="Arvizu 118"/><ref name="trl-retirement">{{cite web|url=http://www.atrl.net/trlarchive/?s=halloffame|title=Hall of Fame|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=The TRL Archive}}</ref><ref>Jackman, Ian ''TRL: the ultimate fan guide''. November 28, 2000. p. 60<U+2013>62. ISBN 0743418506</ref>

"Freak on a Leash" won a Grammy for [[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video|Best Music Video, Short Form]], and received a nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Hard Rock Performance|Best Hard Rock Performance]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/grammys.htm|title= 42nd Grammy Awards&nbsp;<U+2013> 2000|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=Rock on the Net}}</ref> The video also earned nine [[MTV Video Music Awards]] nominations for Video of the Year, Best Rock Video, Breakthrough Video, Best Direction, Best Special Effects, Best Art Direction, Best Cinematography, Best Editing, and Viewer's Choice.<ref name="vma-1999">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1999/mtvvmas.htm|title=1999 MTV Video Music Awards|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=Rock on the Net}}</ref> It eventually won two awards, one being for Best Rock Video and the other for Best Editing.<ref name="Arvizu 118"/><ref>Mancini, Robert (1999-09-09) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429180/19990909/fugees.jhtml?paid=1094 "Korn, Lauryn Hill Among Early VMA Winners"]. MTV. Retrieved 2010-06-28.</ref><ref>(1999-02-04) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430983/19990204/korn.jhtml "Korn 'Freak' Video To Debut On Friday"]. MTV. Retrieved 2010-07-08.</ref> "Freak on a Leash" remains one of Korn's biggest singles on ''Billboard'', having reached number six on [[Alternative Songs]] and number ten on [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Mainstream Rock Songs]].<ref name="US" /> ''Follow the Leader'' is considered by members of Korn to be the band's most commercially<U+2013>successful album,<ref name="Arvizu 118"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=124}}</ref> being certified five-times Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Korn|type=album|title=Follow the Leader}} and having sold almost ten million copies worldwide.<ref name="US">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/korn/chart-history/121196|title=American chart|publisher=[[Billboard charts]]|accessdate=2010-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|pp=119<U+2013>123}}</ref>

===''Issues'' (1999<U+2013>2001)===
The band's fourth album, ''[[Issues (Korn album)|Issues]]'', produced by [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]], was released on November 16, 1999,<ref>Rosli, Adilin [http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-24032396.html "Article: CD REVIEW: Korn's 'Issues'"]. University Wire. HighBeam. 1999-11-16</ref> featuring cover art designed by Alfredo Carlos, who won a contest held for the fans by MTV.<ref name="korn-cover-contest">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430971/19990917/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Asks Fans To Design Next Album Cover|date=1999-09-17|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> ''Issues'' was released during a week of many highly-anticipated records. It debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 with more than 573,000 copies sold,<ref name="issues-first-week">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428109/19991124/dion_celine.jhtml|title=Korn Tops Dre, Celine, Will Smith On Album Chart|date=1999-11-24|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> keeping [[Dr. Dre]]'s album ''[[2001 (album)|2001]]'' and C<U+00E9>line Dion's [[All the Way... A Decade of Song|greatest hits album]] from hitting number one.<ref name="issues-first-week"/><ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r441973|pure_url=yes}} Snoop Dogg - Charts and Awards]. Allmusic. Accessed May 25, 2008.</ref>

To celebrate the album's release, the band performed the record in its entirety in front of a live audience at New York's historic [[Apollo Theater]] and broadcast the concert simultaneously across many radio stations.<ref name="issues-apollo">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430961/19991116/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Fills Apollo With New Sounds, Rabid Fans, And V.I.P.s|date=1999-11-16|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> This performance made Korn the first rock band to ever perform at The Apollo, after [[Buddy Holly]] in the late 1950s.<ref name="imagery"/> This special event featured the [[New York Police Department]] marching [[percussion instrument|drum]] and [[bagpipes|bagpipe]] band conducted by [[Richard Gibbs]] as well as a group of back-up singers to enhance the more melodic choruses Davis used on the album.<ref name="imagery">{{cite book |title=Imagery in sports and physical performance |author1=Anees A. Sheikh |year=1994 |publisher=Baywood Publishing Company |isbn=0895030802 |pages=161<U+2013>164 |accessdate=2010-07-08}}</ref> A snippet of "[[Falling Away from Me]]" was featured on [[RealVideo]] with a brief [[interpretive dance]] by bassist [[Reginald Arvizu]],<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.mtv.com/bands/archive/k/kornfeature99.jhtml
| title = MTV Bands - Archive - K
| publisher = MTV
| archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5rRq7v39b
| archivedate = 2010-07-23<!-- 19:24:26
-->| accessdate = 2010-07-23
| quote = A snippet of the song is available here in RealVideo, complete with a brief interpretive dance from Fieldy.
}}</ref> and also featured on their official website as an [[MP3|MP3 file]], although its release was against the advice of its attorneys and corporate establishment.<ref>Johnson, Tina (1999-10-29) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430966/19991029/korn.jhtml "Korn Offers Free MP3 Of New Single"]. [[MTV]]. Retrieved 2010-07-23.</ref> The album was also promoted by the band's highly successful [[Sick and Twisted Tour]].

Earlier that year, Korn had appeared on an episode of [[South Park]], titled "[[Korn's Groovy Pirate Ghost Mystery]]", in which the first single from ''Issues'', "Falling Away from Me", was premiered.<ref name="issues-south-park">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430968/19991011/korn.jhtml|title=Korn To Premiere New Track During "South Park" Special|date=1999-10-11|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1430962/19991105/korn.jhtml |title=Korn Headed To The Apollo To Unveil "Issues" |date=1999-11-05|accessdate=2010-07-23|author=Robert Mancini |publisher=MTV}}</ref> Korn released two more singles from ''Issues'', "[[Make Me Bad]]" and "[[Somebody Someone]]", both of which fared well on ''Billboard''.<ref name="US" /> Music videos were filmed for all three singles, with long time friend Fred Durst directing "Falling Away from Me", and Martin Weisz directing a concept video for "Make Me Bad", as well as a performance video for "Somebody Someone", which featured the use of [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] effects. Every video was a staple on ''Total Request Live'', two of which made it to retirement.<ref name="trl-retirement" /> ''Issues'' is considered by some critics to be less hip hop-influenced and closer to alternative metal than nu metal.<ref name="amg-issues">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r445043|pure_url=yes}}|title=''Issues'' review|accessdate=2007-01-25|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]}}</ref> It was certified three-times Platinum,{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Korn|type=album|title=Issues}} following up the success of ''Follow the Leader''.<ref name="US"/>

===''Untouchables'' (2002<U+2013>03)===
{{Listen
|filename=Korn - Here to Stay.ogg
|title="Here to Stay" (2002)
|description="[[Here to Stay (Korn song)|Here to Stay]]", the first [[single (music)|single]] from ''[[Untouchables (album)|Untouchables]]'', went on to win Korn a Grammy in Jon Wiederhorn said "Although "Here to Stay" is clearly a scathing commentary on contemporary America, Davis stressed that it's merely a wake-up call, not a cry for action."<ref>{{cite web|last=Wiederhorn |first=Jon |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453609/20020425/korn.jhtml |title=Korn's Jonathan Davis On New Video: 'This Is What Kids Are Taught' - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=2002-04-26 |accessdate=2010-10-13}}</ref>}}

On June 10, 2002, after a year and a half of touring, Korn re-emerged into the media with their fifth album, ''[[Untouchables (album)|Untouchables]]''. It debuted at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 with 434,000 in sales.<ref name="untouchables-first-week">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1455302/20020619/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Can't Kick Eminem From Top Of Billboard Chart|date=2002-06-19|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> The band has blamed [[Warez|Internet piracy]] for the drop in sales, as an unmastered version of the album had leaked three months prior to its official release date.<ref name="untouchables-leak">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453230/20020402/korn.jhtml|title=Shock Jocks Give New Korn LP Premature Premiere, Perturbing Label|date=2002-04-02|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> On April 2, 2002, the [[Shock Jock]]s, an American [[Radio programming|radio program]], began airing songs from ''Untouchables''. After playing a few songs, the broadcasters retrieved a cease-and-desist letter from [[Sony Music Entertainment]]. One broadcaster said "The reason for the premature premiere was to infuriate a rival New York station, which disallows their in-studio guests to appear on 'The Opie and Anthony Show.'"<ref>Joe D'Angelo (2002-04-02). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1453230/20020402/korn.jhtml "Shock Jocks Give New Korn LP Premature Premiere, Perturbing Label"]. MTV.</ref> The release of this album was preceded by a show at the Hammerstein Ballroom in New York, a day prior to the album's release, broadcast digitally throughout movie theatres in the United States.<ref name="untouchables-hammerstein">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1455110/20020611/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Whip Out Maggots, Flames, Crucifix-Emblazoned Dress At NY Concert|date=2002-06-11|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref>

The album contained experiments and styles never previously attempted by Korn. ''Allmusic'' related: "The band is far more experimental this time out, delivering [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]]-like ringing guitars that melt and morph into each other, a mix of [[Metallica]]-esque blastbeats and tight funk drumming from the constantly improving [[David Silveria]], and memorable riffs that take the shape of dark sound structures and offer more than just a collection of chords."<ref>Torreano, Bradley [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r590483|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Untouchables > Overview )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref> The first two videos from ''Untouchables'', "Here to Stay" and "Thoughtless", were directed by the [[Hughes Brothers]].<ref>{{cite album-notes |title="Untouchables (Deluxe Edition)" |albumlink=Untouchables (album) |bandname=Korn |year=2002 |format=Compact Disc |publisher=[[Immortal Records]]/[[Epic Records]] }}</ref> "Here to Stay" earned Korn a Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance.<ref name="grammy-metal">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/grammy/metal.htm|title=Grammy Awards: Best Metal Performance|accessdate=2007-09-03|publisher=Rock on the Net}}</ref> "Here to Stay" peaked at number four on both the Alternative Songs and Mainstream Rock Songs charts.<ref name="US" />

===''Take a Look in the Mirror'', ''Greatest Hits Vol. 1'', Head's departure (2003<U+2013>05)===
Due to the album leaking onto the Internet, ''[[Take a Look in the Mirror]]'' was released on a Friday, November 21, 2003; four days earlier than its original release date.<ref name="mirror leak"/> The album therefore received a weekend's worth of sales, along with a shortage in shipments, both of which resulted in a poor showing on the ''Billboard'' 200. During its first full week, ''Take a Look in the Mirror'' soared ten places from number 19 to number nine, bringing the album's total sales to 179,000. It is the first album where Korn produced the album themselves. The band explained that they want fans to hear the music as it should be.<ref name="mirror leak">D'Angelo, Joe (2003-11-17). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1480466/20031117/korn.jhtml?headlines=true "Korn Releasing Take A Look In The Mirror Early Due To Leak"]. MTV.</ref> The album presented different styles and themes compared to previous albums. Lead vocalist Jonathan Davis related: "The whole album is about love, hate and my hate of people and just losing my mind. The previous albums I did, I think the last three, I was coming from a place of hurt. And I just finally got to the point where I'm done hurting and I'm just pissed off about it now. It's turned back to just sheer hate and anger. And it definitely comes across on the album." [[MTV]] said that Davis convinced his fans that they "will be shocked, particularly with the album's second track, "Break Some Off," which he called 'brutal'."<ref>Moss, Corey (2003-11-10). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1480293/20031110/korn.jhtml "Korn Return To 'Sheer Hate And Anger' For New Album"]. MTV.</ref> Korn released the single "[[Did My Time]]" on July 22, 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472484/20030610/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Do 'Time' For Lara Croft|date=2003-06-11|accessdate=2007-11-30|publisher=MTV}}</ref> which was used to promote the film but did not appear on the soundtrack to ''[[Lara Croft Tomb Raider: The Cradle of Life]]'' due to unspecified legal issues.<ref>''Billboard''. "Hollywood Rocks Its 'Cradle of Life' Soundtrack". 2003-08-02. p. 15.</ref> "Did My Time" gave Korn another Grammy nomination in the Best Metal Performance category.<ref name="grammy-metal" />

Korn released their greatest hits album, ''[[Greatest Hits, Volume 1 (Korn album)|Greatest Hits Vol. 1]]'', on October 5, 2004.<ref>Birchmeier, Jason. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r713235|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 > Overview )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref> The album debuted at number four on ''Billboard'', selling more than 129,000 copies.<ref name="greatest-hits-first-week">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1492244/20041013/strait_george.jhtml|title=George Strait Tops Usher In Billboard Albums Chart Recount|date=2004-10-13|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> This album assembles choice tracks from six Korn studio albums between 1994 and 2003.<ref>(2004-09-24). [http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-828472/Korn-Greatest-Hits-Vol-1.html "Korn: Greatest Hits Vol 1."]. ''[[Music Week]]''.</ref> The first single was a cover of the song "[[Word Up! (song)|Word Up!]]", which was originally composed by the group [[Cameo (band)|Cameo]].<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=song|id=t7265335|pure_url=yes}} "Word Up!"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref> Special editions of the album included a DVD titled ''Korn: Live at [[CBGB]]'' featuring seven select songs from their November 24, 2003 show at CBGB.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=17423 "KORN: 'Live At CBGB's' To Premiere On MTV2"]. Blabbermouth.net. 2003-12-16.</ref>

In early 2005, Brian Welch announced that he would be quitting the band. In front of a crowd of 10,000, in three services at Valley Bible Fellowship in Bakersfield, California, said <U+201C>I was addicted to methamphetamines and tried everything ... rehab, stuff on the Internet, but nothing helped me kick it. I was trying on my own to quit and couldn<U+2019>t do it. I wanted to die. No one knew what I was going through. I could not quit. Church was my last shot. I would sit in church high [on drugs]. I would wonder why people would go up to the front after the service. But one day it was for me. I said [to God], <U+2018>Show me how to quit.'"<ref>Cottrell, Kelli (2005-03-01). [http://www.bpnews.net/bpnews.asp?ID=20247 "Korn<U+2019>s former guitarist says of newfound faith, <U+2018>this is real<U+2019>"]. [[Baptist Press]].</ref><ref name="head-a">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1497313/20050222/korn.jhtml|title=Brian 'Head' Welch Leaves Korn, Citing Moral Objections To Band's Music|date=2005-02-22|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> Since, Welch has released two [[autobiography|Autobiographies]], and released one solo album.<ref>[http://www.cbn.com/cbnmusic/news/091508BrianWelch.aspx "Brian "Head" Welch Releases 'Save Me From Myself'"]. CBN.com. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref>

===''See You on the Other Side'' (2005<U+2013>06)===
Upon completing their record deal with [[Sony BMG|Sony]], Korn partnered with [[EMI]] and signed to [[Virgin Records]]. As part of this innovative arrangement, Virgin paid Korn $25 million upfront in exchange for a share in the profits of their next two studio albums, including tours and merchandising. Virgin also received a 30 percent stake in the band's licensing, ticket sales and other revenue sources.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001096509#/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001096509 "Korn Signs With Virgin"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref><ref>(2007-06-04) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=76054 "Korn Members Discuss Innovative EMI Deal"]. Blabbermouth.net. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref>

{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center
 |quote = It's taking Korn into another dimension for the listener, I think, that takes you to another world. I think it's really emotional, as far as it's not so anger-based. You know, I think it's a more well-rounded emotional journey it kinda takes you on, the listener.
 |source = James "Munky" Shaffer on ''See You on the Other Side''.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=44667 "KORN Guitarist Says New Album Takes Listeners On 'Journey' "]. Blabbernouth.net. 2005-11-23.</ref>
 |width = 30%
 |align = right
}}

The band's first album for Virgin, ''[[See You on the Other Side (Korn album)|See You on the Other Side]]'', was released on December 6, 2005,<ref>Harris, Chris (2005-11-17). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1513980/20051117/korn.jhtml?headlines=true "Korn Taking European Fans To Other Side ... Of The Atlantic"]. MTV.</ref> and debuted at number three on the ''Billboard'' 200,<ref>(2010-08-11) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=144389 "Korn: New Video Interview With Ray Luzier"]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref> scanning close to 221,000 copies.<ref name="other-side-first-week">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1518100/20051214/eminem.jhtml|title=Eminem Scores Fourth #1 Bow With Curtain Call|date=2005-12-14|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> The album managed to stay in the top half of the ''Billboard'' 200 for thirty-four consecutive weeks.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200#/album/korn/see-you-on-the-other-side/744735 See You on the Other Side"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref> The first single from the album, "[[Twisted Transistor]]", was accompanied by a music video directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]] in which hip hop artists [[Xzibit]], [[Lil' Jon]], [[Snoop Dogg]], and [[David Banner]] portray Korn.<ref>Moss, Corey (2005-10-06) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1511049/20051006/korn.jhtml "Lil Jon, Snoop, Xzibit, David Banner Star In New Korn Video"]. MTV.</ref> The single itself peaked at number three on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Mainstream Rock Songs, Korn's highest entry thus far, and number nine on Alternative Songs.<ref>''Billboard'' 2005-12-10, pp. 42, 54</ref> The second single, "[[Coming Undone]]", had its performance-based video directed by [[Little X]],<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/videos/korn/77582/coming-undone.jhtml Coming Undone | Korn | Music Video | MTV]. Retrieved 2010-05-13.</ref><ref>{{cite album-notes |title="Coming Undone Wit It Enhanced Dual Disc VCD" |albumlink=Coming Undone wit It |bandname=Korn |year=2006 |format=Compact Disc |publisher=[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]/[[EMI]] }}</ref> who previously helmed hip hop and [[Rhythm and Blues|R&B]] videos.<ref>[[IMDbName:1962311|"Little X"]]. IMBd. Retrieved 2010-08-12.</ref> ''See You on the Other Side'' was certified Platinum,{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Korn|type=album|title=See You on the Other Side}} and by mid-2007 had sold over 1.2 million copies worldwide.<ref>''Billboard''. 2007-06-09. Jun 9, 2007. p. 22.</ref>

Korn held a press conference at the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] on January 13, 2006, announcing the ''See You on the Other Side'' Tour.<ref name="other-side-tour">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1520757/20060113/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Announce Tour Dates While Surrounded By Dead Celebrities|date=2006-01-13|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> [[10 Years (band)|10 Years]] and [[Mudvayne]] were selected to open all dates of the trek, which kicked off in their hometown of Bakersfield, on what Mayor Harvey Hall officially declared as "Korn Day", February 26.<ref name="korn-day">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1524956/20060227/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Rock Hometown, Have Street Named After Them On 'Official Korn Day'|date=2006-02-27|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> The resurrection of their Family Values Tour was announced on April 18, 2006, which featured co-headliners [[Deftones]], [[Stone Sour]], [[Flyleaf]], and the Japanese metal group, [[Dir En Grey]] on the main stage.<ref name="fvt-2006">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1528963/20060418/korn.jhtml|title=Korn Resurrect Family Values Tour With Deftones, Stone Sour|date=2006-04-18|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> Korn and [[Evanescence]] co-headlined the 2007 edition, with [[Atreyu (band)|Atreyu]], 2006 alumni Flyleaf, [[Hellyeah]], and [[Trivium (band)|Trivium]] rounding out the main stage.<ref name="fvt-2007">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1555661/20070326/korn.jhtml|title=Korn, Evanescence, Hellyeah Top Family Values Tour Bill|date=2007-03-26|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref>

While promoting ''See You on the Other Side'' in Europe, Jonathan Davis was diagnosed with [[idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura]], a blood platelet disorder that hospitalized him for the weekend and prevented him from performing at the renowned [[Download Festival]].<ref name="jd-illness-a">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=53521|title=KORN Frontman To Sit Out U.K.'s DOWNLOAD Festival, Guest Singers To Step In|date=2006-06-10|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=[[Blabbermouth]]}}</ref> Despite the illness, the band still performed, with guest singers including [[Corey Taylor]] of the [[nu metal]] band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] and [[hard rock]] band [[Stone Sour]], [[Skindred]]'s Benji Webbe, and [[Avenged Sevenfold]]'s [[M. Shadows]]. This led to Korn canceling the rest of their European bill for 2006,<ref name="jd-illness-b">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=53619|title=KORN: European Tour Officially Cancelled|date=2006-06-13|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=[[Blabbermouth]]}}</ref> including the [[Hellfest Summer Open Air]]. It was originally unknown to the public what his ailment was, but the singer revealed in a letter to fans that he was "dangerously low on blood platelets and at a high risk of death from a hemorrhage if the problem was not treated".<ref name="jd-illness-c">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=53594|title=KORN Frontman JONATHAN DAVIS: 'I Should Be Healthy To Play In A Few Weeks'|date=2006-06-12|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=[[Blabbermouth]]}}</ref>

===Untitled album, ''MTV Unplugged'', David Silveria's departure (2006<U+2013>08)===
[[Image:Korn.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Korn at [[Rock am Ring and Rock im Park#Past dates & headliners|Rock am Ring 2007]].]]
In early December 2006 it was announced that founding drummer [[David Silveria]] would be taking an indefinite <U+201C>temporary hiatus<U+201D> from the band.<ref>(2006-12-19). [http://www.therockradio.com/2006/12/korn-not-breaking-up-says-jonathan.html "Korn "not breaking up" says Jonathan Davis"]. [[The Rock Radio Network|The Rock Radio.com]].</ref><ref name="reuters">Cohen, Jonathan (2006-12-14). [http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKN1420378520061215 "Korn tapes 'Unplugged,' drummer takes a break"]. [[Reuters]].</ref> Korn then performed at the MTV studios in [[Times Square]] on December 9, 2006, for the [[MTV Unplugged]] series, which was broadcasted on February 23, 2007, through MTV.com and on March 2, 2007, across North American, South American, European and Asian MTV stations.<ref>(2007-02-20) [http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-6267474/MTV-Unplugged-KoRn-to-Debut.html " 'MTV Unplugged: KoRn' to Debut on MTV.com on February 23 and On-Air on March 2 at 11:30PM ET/PT"]. [[PR Newswire]]. [[Gale (publisher)|Goliath]].</ref> Korn played a 14-song [[acoustic music|acoustic]] set complete with guest appearances by [[The Cure]] and [[Amy Lee]] of [[Evanescence]].<ref>Harris, Chris (2006-12-13). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1547908/20061213/korn.jhtml?rsspartner=rssSimplePie "Korn Quiet Down With The Cure, Amy Lee For 'MTV Unplugged'"]. MTV. Retrieved 2010-08-13.</ref> The performance was eventually cut down to 11 songs for the album, two of which did not air on MTV. Sales of nearly 51,000 brought ''[[MTV Unplugged: Korn]]'' to number nine in its first week out.<ref name="unplugged-first-week">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1554573/20070314/notorious_big.jhtml|title=Notorious B.I.G. Is The Greatest: Hits LP Debuts At #1|date=2007-03-14|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref>

Korn's [[Untitled Korn album|untitled album]] was released on July 31, 2007, debuting at number two on ''Billboard'' with 123,000 copies sold in its first week.<ref name="untitled-first-week">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1566617/20070808/common.jhtml|title=Common Creams Korn, Coasts To First Billboard #1|date=2007-08-08|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=MTV}}</ref> It concluded Korn's deal with Virgin Records,<ref>(2010-03-26) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=137467 "KORN Frontman Confirms ROADRUNNER Deal"]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref> and features touring keyboardist [[Zac Baird]], giving the tracks a deeper, atmospheric sound.<ref name="untitled-billboard">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003592846|title=Korn Goes Experimental, Vents Anger On New Album|date=2007-06-01|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]''}}</ref> Drumming duties were left up to [[Terry Bozzio]], and [[Bad Religion]]'s [[Brooks Wackerman]], as David Silveria went on a hiatus.<ref name="untitled-bozzio">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=65008|title=KORN Is 'Having A Lot Of Fun' Working With Drummer TERRY BOZZIO|date=2007-01-09|accessdate=2007-10-03|publisher=[[Blabbermouth]]}}</ref> [[Joey Jordison]] from [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] played drums during Korn's live shows until the permanent addition of [[Ray Luzier]], confirming David's departure.<ref>{{cite news |title = For The Record: Quick News On Nelly Furtado, Lindsay Lohan, Sanjaya, Korn, Ciara, DJ Drama & More |publisher = MTV |date = 2007-04-20 |url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1557693/20070420/furtado_nelly.jhtml |accessdate = 2005-07-22}}</ref><ref>(2008-02-27) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=91725 "KORN Bassist Says RAY LUZIER Is 'My Favorite Drummer I've Ever Played With' "]. Blabbermouth.net</ref><ref>(2008-04-28) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=95816 "RAY LUZIER's KORN Audition Posted Online"]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref> "[[Evolution (Korn song)|Evolution]]" and "[[Hold On (Korn song)|Hold On]]" were released as singles to promote the untitled album. They each charted on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Mainstream Rock Songs chart at number four and number nine, respectively.<ref name="US" /> A third single, "Kiss", had a limited release in April 2008.<ref>[http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16698#28 FMQB Airplay Archive] FMQB. Retrieved 2010-02-17.</ref><ref>(2008-04-08). [http://www.hiphop-elements.com/article/read/4/20733/1/ "KORN: 'The Very Best Of' Collection Due This Month"]. HHE</ref> Korn covered the song "Kidnap the Sandy Claws" in 2007, which was originally written by [[Paul Reubens]], [[Catherine O'Hara]], and Danny Elfman. It was released on ''[[Nightmare Revisited]]''.<ref>[http://hangout.altsounds.com/reviews/104831-nightmare-revisited-album.html "NIGHTMARE REVISITED &#91; ALBUM&#93;"]. ALTSounds. 2009-01-27.</ref>

===''Korn III: Remember Who You Are'' (2008<U+2013>2010)===
{{Listen
|filename=Korn - Oildale (Leave Me Alone).ogg
|title="Oildale (Leave Me Alone)" (2010)
|description=[[Roadrunner Records]] said that "Oildale (Leave Me Alone)" "buzzes with an eerie clean guitar that slowly gives way to a steamrolling bass and riff assault."<ref>(2010-04-24). [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=139070 KORN: 'Remember Who You Are' Track Listing Revealed]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref>
}}
[[Ubisoft]] reported in October 2008 that Korn had "written and recorded an original song inspired by Ubisoft's "[[Haze (video game)|Haze]]" video game, simply entitled "[[Haze (song)|Haze]]",<ref>{{cite news|author=Sean Ridgeley |url=http://www.neoseeker.com/news/7943-korn-promote-haze-with-new-song/|date=2008-04-25|title=Korn promote Haze with new song|publisher=Neoseeker News}}</ref> which was released on April 22, 2008.<ref>(2008-04-23) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=95543 "KORN: 'Haze' Video Available"]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref> Korn also released a live DVD, ''[[Korn: Live in Montreux 2004]]'', one of their performances with former guitarist Brian Welch on May 12, 2008.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1364059|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Live at Montreux 2004 > Overview )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-13.</ref> Additionally, a second greatest hits compilation titled ''Playlist: The Very Best of Korn'' was released on April 29, 2008.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/korn/albums.jhtml "Korn | Album Discography and Track Listings"]. MTV. Retrieved 2010-08-13.</ref> Korn announced in February 2009 that they were playing at the Rock Fest in [[Cadott, Wisconsin]], as well as the third annual [[Rock on the Range]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]].<ref>[http://www.rockontherange.com/docs/pressrelease.pdf "Rock On The Range 2009: Rock Festical Returns Saturday, May 16 and Sunday, May 17 to Columbus, Ohio's Crew Stadium"]. RockOnTheRange.com. Retrieved 2010-08-13.</ref> The band was also confirmed for the [[Download 2009|Download Festival]] taking place in the UK, sub-headlining to [[Faith No More]], as well as the simultaneous German festivals [[Rock am Ring and Rock im Park]].<ref>(2009-02-04) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=113773 "KORN, KILLSWITCH ENGAGE, MARILYN MANSON Confirmed For ROCK AM RING/ROCK IM PARK Festival"]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref>

{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center
 |quote = ...Korn III: Remember Who You Are isn<U+2019>t a numbering device, it signifies an opening of another phase in Korn<U+2019>s career. Somehow, the band has bypassed a Korn II altogether in their discography, but it<U+2019>s commonly acknowledged that the tail-end of the 2000s found the group floundering a bit, going so far as to flirt with the Matrix in an attempt to figure out which direction to go now that they<U+2019>ve hit middle age.
 |source = Stephen Thomas Erlewine on ''[[Korn III: Remember Who You Are]]''<ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=korn-iii-remember-who-you-are-r1822420/review|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Korn III: Remember Who You Are > Overview )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-10-14.</ref>
 |width = 30%
 |align = left
}}
In a [[YouTube]] video, bassist Fieldy affirmed that the "Chi Song" project he was putting together (released as "[[A Song for Chi]]") which was released recently to raise money for [[Deftones]] bassist [[Chi Cheng (musician)|Chi Cheng]] who was in a car crash in late 2008, which resulted in him falling into a coma.<ref name="fieldy">[http://modlife.com/korn/news/4/6282/fieldy_writing_instrumental_song_for_deftones_chi_cheng Fieldy writing instrumental song for Deftones' Chi Cheng] modlife.com/korn. 2009-05-18.</ref> Fieldy revealed that [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]] guitarist [[Jim Root]], [[Clint Lowery]] of [[Sevendust]], drummer [[Dave McClain (drummer)|Dave McClain]] of [[Machine Head (band)|Machine Head]] and former Korn guitarist Brian "Head" Welch, would be some of the many musicians playing on the song.<ref name="fieldy"/>

Along with the announcement of the [[Ballroom Blitz Tour]] on March 15, 2010, the title for the new album was revealed as ''[[Korn III: Remember Who You Are]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://modlife.com/korn/news|title=Korn Announces Jagermeister Music Tour|date=March 15, 2010|accessdate=March 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whiplash.net/materias/news_865/104522-korn.html |title=Korn: anunciada nova turn<U+00EA>, "Ballroom Blitz Tour" - Novidades (Not<U+00ED>cia) |publisher=Whiplash.net |date= |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref> Later that month, Munky announced that Korn has officially signed to [[Roadrunner Records]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theprp.com/2010/03/30/news/korn-officially-sign-with-roadrunner-records/|title=Korn Officially Sign With Roadrunner Records|date=2010-03-30|accessdate=2010-07-02|publisher=The PRP}}</ref> Jonathan Davis related: "We're going to go to Roadrunner. [It is] real exciting for us, too, because they're one of the last record companies to let you do what you want to do and, um, all the great bands around are on that label and everything seems to just work out right and it seems like a good home for us right now."<ref>(2010-03-26) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=137467 "Korn Frontman Confirms ROADRUNNER Deal"]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref> Korn announced the track listing on April 24, 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=139070|title=Korn: 'Remember Who You Are' Track Listing Revealed|date=2010-04-24|accessdate=2010-07-02|publisher=Roadrunner Records}}</ref> and May 5, 2010, Roadrunner Records released a promotional single titled "[[Oildale (Leave Me Alone)]]", for streaming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=139591|title=KORN: New Song Available For Streaming|date=2010-05-05|accessdate=2010-07-02|publisher=Roadrunner Records}}</ref> The single was simultaneously released for radio airplay, peaking at number ten on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Mainstream Rock Songs and number twenty-nine on Alternative Songs.<ref name="US" /> Korn released the music video for "Oildale (Leave Me Alone)" on May 31, 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=140938|title=Korn: 'Oildale' Video Released |date=2010-05-31|accessdate=2010-07-02|publisher=Roadrunner Records}}</ref> and on July 1, 2010, Korn played "Oildale (Leave Me Alone)" and premiered a follow-up single, "[[Let the Guilt Go]]," on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedeadbolt.com/news/107705/korn_jimmy_kimmel_news.php|title=Korn to Rock Jimmy Kimmel Live on July 1|publisher=The deadBolt|author=Reg Seeton|accessdate=2010-07-02}}</ref> The band released ''Korn III: Remember Who You Are'' in the US on July 13, 2010.<ref>Stephen Thomas Erlewine. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1822420|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic. ((( Korn iii: Remember who you are > Overview )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-15.</ref> It debuted at its peak of number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 with 63,000 purchases reported.<ref>Keith Caulfield (2010-07-21). [http://www.billboard.com/album/korn/korn-iii-remember-who-you-are/1378860/review#/news/eminem-s-recovery-tops-billboard-200-for-1004105318.story "Eminem's 'Recovery' Tops Billboard 200 for a Fourth Week"]. ''Billboard''.</ref> Korn performed "Let the Guilt Go" on the [[late-night television]] talk show ''[[Lopez Tonight]]'' on August 24, 2010.<ref>(2010-08-25) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=145062 "Korn Performs On 'Lopez Tonight'; Video Available"]. Blabbermouth.net</ref><ref>(2010-08-25) [http://www.lopeztonight.com/episode_recaps_and_highlights/korn_really_lets_the_guilt_go.php "Korn Really Lets the Guilt Go!"]. Lopez Tonight.</ref><ref name="let the guilt go video">(2010-08-27). [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=145195 "Korn: 'Let The Guilt Go' Video To Premiere Next Week"]. Blabbermouth.net</ref> The song's music video premiered on September 2, 2010.<ref name="let the guilt go video"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smnnews.com/2010/09/02/korn-let-the-guilt-go-video-premiere/ |title=KORN: <U+201C>Let the Guilt Go<U+201D> Video Premiere |publisher=SMNnews.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/news/article/0,,7524162,00.html |title=ARTISTdirect to Premiere Korn "Let the Guilt Go" Video Next Week - ARTISTdirect News |publisher=Artistdirect.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref> Korn will be co-headlining the [[Music as a Weapon|Music as a Weapon V]] tour  with [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]] during winter 2011. The tour will also feature supporting acts [[Sevendust]] and [[In This Moment]].<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=149742 "It's Official: DISTURBED, KORN, SEVENDUST, IN THIS MOMENT To Take Part In 'Music As A Weapon V'"]. Blabbermouth.net. 2010-11-21.</ref>

===Next album (2011<U+2013>present)===
According to guitarist [[James Shaffer|James "Munky" Shaffer]], Korn has begun writing new material for their next album. He explains, "We have probably three songs we wrote a couple, two, three months ago. We went into the studio, we wrote some songs, Jon demoed the songs on his computer, and then we took them into the studio and played them live and tweaked them a little bit. Then we put those down and recorded them. They're cool. They kind of remind me a little bit of the [[Soundgarden]] style, that sort of Seattle sound<U+2026> just one of them. The other songs are sort of different, a little more in the experimental stage right now. I don't want to give too much away. We're definitely moving forward, we'll probably start recording in April to try and finetune this sound we're developing."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=152668 |title=BLABBERMOUTH.NET - KORN Begins Work On New Material |publisher=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-09}}</ref> It has been rumored across the web that Brendan O'Brien will be producing the album. He previously worked with the band on their fourth studio album, ''Issues''. It was also stated last year by Jonathan Davis in an interview with [[ARTISTdirect]] that one track recorded for the album features acoustic guitar <U+2014> a first for Korn <U+2014> tentatively titled "Lullaby for a Sadist".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/jonathan-davis-of-korn-talks-disturbed-tour-discovering-the-cure-acid-bath-and-more/8167471 |title=Jonathan Davis of Korn Talks Disturbed Tour, Discovering The Cure, Acid Bath and More - ARTISTdirect News |publisher=Artistdirect.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-09}}</ref>

The band will be making their second [[Rock on the Range]] apperance on May 21, 2011, at [[Crew Stadium]], in [[Columbus, OH]].

==Style==
The band has stated that their primary influences include [[Sepultura]], [[Faith No More]], [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Rage Against the Machine]], [[Slayer]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Primus (band)|Primus]], [[Tool (band)|Tool]],  [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]], [[Mr. Bungle]], [[Biohazard (band)|Biohazard]], [[Metallica]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[Pantera]], [[Beastie Boys]], [[Black Sabbath]], and [[Jane's Addiction]].<ref name="arvizu 36"/><ref name="allmusic"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=40}}</ref> Much of their work has been inspired by [[hip hop music]], as suggested in the [[cover song]] "[[Wicked (song)|Wicked]]", and "[[All in the Family (song)|All in the Family]]".<ref>{{Harvnb|Arvizu|2009|p=80}}</ref><ref name="Small 1998 58">{{Harvnb|Small|1998|p=58}}</ref><ref>"Reviews". ''Spin''. 1998-10. pp. 135-136</ref>

They are the first band to be labeled as [[nu metal]], starting the [[New Wave of American Heavy Metal]].<ref>{{cite book |last=McIver |first=Joel |title=Nu-metal: The Next Generation of Rock & Punk |year=2002 |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=0711992096 |pages=10; 12 |chapter=How did we get to nu-metal from old metal? }}</ref> Alongside this genre, the band has also been labeled as [[rap metal]], [[Rap rock|thrash rap]], and pimp rock.<ref>''Guitar World Presents Nu-Metal'' Hal Leonard Corp, 2002. p9. 69-71. ISBN 0634032879</ref> Their debut album mixed [[heavy metal music|metal]], [[hard rock|rock]], [[hip-hop]], [[Groove (music)|groove]], and [[Consonance and dissonance|dissonance]]. Alongside nu metal, the band is often labeled as heavy metal, [[alternative metal]], [[post grunge]], and [[rap metal]].<ref name="allmusic">Jason Ankeny, Bradley Torreano. [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p144403|pure_url=yes}} "allmusic ((( Korn > Biography )))"]. Allmusic. Retrieved 2010-08-29.</ref> Their lyrics focus on pain and personal alienation rather than traditional heavy metal themes.<ref>{{cite book |last=McIver |first=Joel |title=Nu-metal: The Next Generation of Rock & Punk |year=2002 |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=0711992096 |pages=12<U+2013>13 |chapter=How is nu-metal different from old metal? }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kahn-Harris |first1=Keith |title=Extreme metal: music and culture on the edge |year=2007 |publisher=[[Berg Publishers]] |isbn=1845203992 |page=1 |chapter=Introduction: From heavy metal to extreme metal }}</ref> In ''Nu-metal: The Next Generation of Rock & Punk'', Korn was marked as the third biggest nu metal band in the world.<ref>{{cite book |last=McIver |first=Joel |title=Nu-metal: The Next Generation of Rock & Punk |year=2002 |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=0711992096 |page=17}}</ref>

The band's debut album warranted a [[Parental Advisory]] label solely because of the album's lyrics. Many of Korn's first works are based on early experiences. The song "[[Daddy (Korn song)|Daddy]]" was described by lead singer [[Jonathan Davis]] "When I was a kid, I was being abused by somebody else and I went to my parents and told them about it, and they thought I was lying and joking around. They never did shit about it. They didn't believe it was happening to their son.... I don't really like to talk about that song. This is as much as I've ever talked about it..."<ref name="arnopp"/><ref>{{cite news | title =Courtney Love claims Britney was molested by her father| url = http://article.wn.com/view/2009/11/26/Courtney_Love_claims_Britney_was_molested_by_her_father_i/ | publisher = WorldNews | date = 2009-11-26 | archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5t2VdUs9v | archivedate = 2010-09-26 }}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Small|1998|p=18}}</ref> "Kill You" was written in spite of Davis's experiences as a child with his step mother.<ref>{{Harvnb|Small|1998|p=10}}</ref> ''Follow the Leader'' marked the first album where the majority of the lyrics did not have origins relating to early occurrences, with songs like "Justin" and "Pretty" written about incidents occurring during adulthood.<ref name="Small 1998 58"/>

Many of Korn's songs do not include a [[guitar solo]]. [[Bass guitar|Bassist]] Reginald Arvizu plays his instrument using both the techniques of [[Fingerstyle guitar|fingerstyle]] and [[slapping]]. Jonathan Davis was said by Doug Small to be "the eye of the storm around which the music of Korn rages."<ref name="Small 1998 5">{{Harvnb|Small|1998|p=5}}</ref> Small described the band as "a basket-case full of contradictions."<ref name="Small 1998 5"/> Although the band virtually had no support by [[television]] or by [[radio broadcasting]] in its first four years, Korn would go on to influence [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Vanilla Ice]], [[Evanescence]], [[Seether]], [[Machine Head (band)|Machine Head]], [[One Minute Silence]], [[Kittie]], [[Endo (band)|Endo]], [[Taproot (band)|Taproot]], [[Mudvayne]], [[Crazy Town]], [[Otep]], [[System of a Down]], [[Hoobastank]], [[Linkin Park]], [[Five Pointe O]], [[Lacuna Coil]], [[Chris Volz]], [[Videodrone]], [[Theory of a Deadman]], [[Thousand Foot Krutch]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Breaking Benjamin]], [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[Bleed the Sky (band)|Bleed the Sky]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Coal Chamber]], [[Emmure]], [[Staind]], [[Suicide Silence]], [[Cold (band)|Cold]], [[Impending Doom]], [[Limp Bizkit]], [[Three Days Grace]] and [[Flyleaf]].<ref name="allmusic"/><ref>{{Cite book |last = Arnopp |first = Jason |title = Slipknot: Inside the Sickness, Behind the Masks |publisher = Ebury |year = 2001 |isbn = 0091879337|pages= 6<U+2013>7}}</ref> Korn also created a fan-basis described by both Doug Small and [[Eaton Corporation|Eaton Entertainment]] as extremely loyal.<ref name="R-U">{{cite video |title=Korn <U+2014> Unauthorized: R-U Ready |format=DVD |language=English |publisher=[[Eaton Corporation|Eaton Entertainment]] |accessdate=2010-08-02 }}</ref>

==Criticism and controversy==
===Vulgarity in lyrics===
Prior to the release of 1998's ''[[Follow the Leader (Korn album)|Follow the Leader]]'', Gretchen Plewes, a [[Zeeland, Michigan|Zeeland]] high school assistant principal, said in an interview for a [[Michigan]] newspaper that the music is "indecent, vulgar, obscene and intends to be insulting" after giving a student a one-day suspension for wearing a shirt with the Korn logo on it.<ref name="t shirt">Ross, Mike (98-09-17) [http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/K/Korn/1998/09/17/746668.html "Kids like their Korn"] ''Canoe''. Retrieved 2010-03-20.</ref> [[WBBL-FM|WKLQ]] was filmed giving away hundreds of free Korn T-shirts, which were donated by the band, outside the school. [[Ottawa County, Michigan|Ottawa]] County policemen helped hand out shirts as well.<ref>Small 1998 p. 50</ref> The student who was suspended, Eric VanHoven, was interviewed by [[MTV]], and said that he had worn the shirt "because it made him look cooliolishish.<ref>(1998-03-10). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431010/19980310/korn.jhtml "Update: Korn T-Shirt Flap Begs Question "What's In A Name?"]. MTV.</ref> Korn filed a [[cease and desist]] order against Plewes and the school district for their comments. They also threatened with a multi-million lawsuit, but both files were dropped due to the band member's personal lives.<ref>Small 1998 p. 52</ref>

===Former band members===
In September 2009, Korn guitarist Munky, in an interview with Altitude TV, alleged that the band had denied a request by Welch to rejoin the group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=126966 |title=BLABBERMOUTH.NET - Ex-KORN Guitarist HEAD Allegedly Asks To Come Back To The Band, Gets Denied |publisher=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antimusic.com/news/09/sep/15Head_Wants_Back_In_Korn.shtml |title=Head Wants Back In Korn? - Korn News @ |publisher=Antimusic.com |date=2009-09-15 |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref> Welch denied the claims via his [[Myspace]], stating that Korn had been asking him to rejoin but he had turned down the offers after Jonathan Davis and Munky had refused to meet him when Welch visited Fieldy socially. He also claimed that for four years he had not been paid [[royalties]] due to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antimusic.com/news/09/sep/16Head_Addresses_Korn_Rejection_Claim.shtml |title=Head Addresses Korn Rejection Claim - Brian Head Welch and Korn News @ |publisher=Antimusic.com |date=2009-09-16 |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref><ref>(2009-09-28) [http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/brian_welch_backlashes_to_comments_about_rejoining_korn.html "Brian Welch Backlashes To Comments About Rejoining Korn"]. Ultimate-guitar.com/ Retrieved 2010-10-14</ref><ref>(2009-09-15) [http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=127015 "Former KORN Guitarist Sets Record Straight Regarding Claim He Asked To Rejoin Band"]. Blabbermouth.net.</ref> Weeks later, in reference to Korn's early albums, Davis stated in an interview with pulseoftheradio that Welch had not contributed to writing material because of his drug usage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=127780 |title=BLABBERMOUTH.NET - KORN Frontman Says HEAD, SILVERIA 'Weren't Really There' During Songwriting For Early Albums |publisher=Roadrunnerrecords.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-17}}</ref> </blockquote>

